05221nam a22008175i 9789048540228DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485402287 a10.1515/97890485402282doi  a(DE-B1597)589506  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aN6757b.W66 2021 7aART0650002bisacsh04a709.03422300aWomen Artists in the Early Modern Courts of Europe :bc. 1450-1700 /ced. by Tanja L. Jones. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (218 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aVisual and Material Culture, 1300 –1700 ;v3000tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Figures -- tAcknowledgements -- t1. Introduction: Women Artists in the Early Modern Courts of Europe, c. 1450–1700 -- t2. Female Court Artists: Women’s Career Strategies in the Courts of the Early Modern Period -- t3. Caterina van Hemessen in the Habsburg Court of Mary of Hungary -- t4. Sofonisba Anguissola, a Painter and a Ladyin- Waiting -- t5. Creative Reproductions: Diana Mantuana and Printmaking at Court -- t6. ‘Una persona dependente alla Serenissima Gran Duchessa’ : Female Embroiderers and Lacemakers between the courts of Florence and France -- t7. Life at Court: Luisa Roldán in Madrid 1689–1706 -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume presents the first collection of essays dedicated to women as producers of visual and material culture in the Early Modern European courts, offering fresh insights into the careers of, among others, Caterina van Hemessen, Sofonisba Anguissola, Luisa Roldán, and Diana Mantuana. Also considered are groups of female makers, such as ladies-in-waiting at the seventeenth-century Medici court. Chapters address works by women who occupied a range of social and economic positions within and around the courts and across media, including paintings, sculpture, prints, and textiles. Both individually and collectively, the texts deepen understanding of the individual artists and courts highlighted and, more broadly, consider the variety of experiences of female makers across traditional geographic and chronological distinctions. The book is also accompanied by the Global Makers: Women Artists in the Early Modern Courts digital humanities project (www.globalmakers.ua.edu), extending and expanding the work begun here.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArtzEuropexHistory. 0aWomen artistszEurope. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aART / Women Artists.2bisacsh  awomen, artists, early modern, Renaissance, courts.1 aCourts, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGamberini, Cecilia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall-van den Elsen, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Tanja L, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Tanja L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMaurer, Maria F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aModesti, Adelina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStrunck, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074322708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2z978311074335740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978904854022840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978904854022842